reviews_data.review_text: I had the espresso flight and I was very impressed by the service and quality of the coffee! Would definitely recommend to anyone looking for a good atmosphere and great espresso.

My one star overall relates to the owner. My five stars for service relates to the staff. As a Waterbean Coffee customer since 2016, I'm one of many (approx 15% of the Huntersville store) longtime customers on the cusp of finding another business to patronize. The owner, Tony, has made the unwise decision to, not only refuse to keep his loose leaf tea stock in supply, but he's also chosen to ignore the countless emails, Facebook messages (he removed a message from another longtime Waterbean customer, and he will likely remove this comment) and in-person questions his AMAZING staff has had to deal with... all because he doesn't understand that loyalists have built his business and financed his multiple locations in the greater CLT area. The Hunterville location is now down to just ONE black tea (and this has been the case for weeks) and the staff are unable to tell customers if or when teas will ever be reordered. If Tony can afford to lose 15% of his Huntersville business, this complaint is likely to fall on deaf ears. But, we're in a time of responsible and responsive business ownership. You will lose what we helped you build if you insist on disrespecting our loyalty.  We kept Waterbean alive during Covid. We packed all locations when a police officer's life was taken and his family needed money (which Waterbean donated from one day's sales). We've tolerated price increases, rental fees for the conference room spaces and DISCONTINUING the discount loyalty program (‼️). That's what loyalists do. And what thanks do we get for our loyalty? No supply for the tea demand and forcing Waterbean staff to deal with endless questions about when tea will be restocked. I understand P&L. I also understand that opening multiple mostly-empty stores all over CLT shouldn't create a penalty for Huntersville store lifers. I've spent thousands of dollars supporting this small business. Stock the tea, Tony.  And, if you're a customer with a favorite Waterbean drink, be forewarned: Your hard-earned money spent supporting Tony's business could be off the menu if he can squeeze another drop out of a penny. Get yourself together, Tony. Loyalty is not guaranteed and ignoring your revenue base is a catastrophic business decision. Do better.

reviews_data.owner_answer:
Hello Christine,

Thank you for your feedback regarding the Americano you had. As you may already know, an Americano is made with espresso and water, and our espresso is carefully roasted and calibrated to taste great on its own without any additions. Therefore, diluting the espresso with water will result in a lighter taste. If you prefer a stronger flavor, we recommend trying our #4 espresso next time, which is better suited for an Americano.

Regarding the extra charge for plant-based milk, we apologize for any inconvenience caused. The reason for the additional charge is that plant-based alternatives are significantly more expensive for us to source, approximately four times more than dairy milk. We do not incorporate this cost into our pricing and keep the extra charge as low as possible. We hope you understand.

Lastly, we appreciate your feedback on our staff, and we will be addressing this matter internally. Thank you for bringing this to our attention.

reviews_data.owner_answer: Hi Olga, we're really sorry about your experience today. Our staff should able to clearly explained to you that our Pour Over is one size only. This is the reason for the inconsistency in the amount of liquid you see in your cup. If you don't like the coffee please feel free to let our staff know to choose another type of coffee and make you another one. Again we're really sorry about this and hope you have a great afternoon friend!

My one star overall relates to the owner. My five stars for service relates to the staff. As a Waterbean Coffee customer since 2016, I'm one of many (approx 15% of the Huntersville store) longtime customers on the cusp of finding another business to patronize. The owner, Tony, has made the unwise decision to, not only refuse to keep his loose leaf tea stock in supply, but he's also chosen to ignore the countless emails, Facebook messages (he removed a message from another longtime Waterbean customer, and he will likely remove this comment) and in-person questions his AMAZING staff has had to deal with... all because he doesn't understand that loyalists have built his business and financed his multiple locations in the greater CLT area. The Hunterville location is now down to just ONE black tea (and this has been the case for weeks) and the staff are unable to tell customers if or when teas will ever be reordered. If Tony can afford to lose 15% of his Huntersville business, this complaint is likely to fall on deaf ears. But, we're in a time of responsible and responsive business ownership. You will lose what we helped you build if you insist on disrespecting our loyalty.  We kept Waterbean alive during Covid. We packed all locations when a police officer's life was taken and his family needed money (which Waterbean donated from one day's sales). We've tolerated price increases, rental fees for the conference room spaces and DISCONTINUING the discount loyalty program (‼️). That's what loyalists do. And what thanks do we get for our loyalty? No supply for the tea demand and forcing Waterbean staff to deal with endless questions about when tea will be restocked. I understand P&L. I also understand that opening multiple mostly-empty stores all over CLT shouldn't create a penalty for Huntersville store lifers. I've spent thousands of dollars supporting this small business. Stock the tea, Tony.  And, if you're a customer with a favorite Waterbean drink, be forewarned: Your hard-earned money spent supporting Tony's business could be off the menu if he can squeeze another drop out of a penny. Get yourself together, Tony. Loyalty is not guaranteed and ignoring your revenue base is a catastrophic business decision. Do better.

reviews_data.owner_answer:
Hello Christine,

Thank you for your feedback regarding the Americano you had. As you may already know, an Americano is made with espresso and water, and our espresso is carefully roasted and calibrated to taste great on its own without any additions. Therefore, diluting the espresso with water will result in a lighter taste. If you prefer a stronger flavor, we recommend trying our #4 espresso next time, which is better suited for an Americano.

Regarding the extra charge for plant-based milk, we apologize for any inconvenience caused. The reason for the additional charge is that plant-based alternatives are significantly more expensive for us to source, approximately four times more than dairy milk. We do not incorporate this cost into our pricing and keep the extra charge as low as possible. We hope you understand.

Lastly, we appreciate your feedback on our staff, and we will be addressing this matter internally. Thank you for bringing this to our attention.

reviews_data.owner_answer: Hi Olga, we're really sorry about your experience today. Our staff should able to clearly explained to you that our Pour Over is one size only. That's around 10oz-12oz depending on the type of coffee. We usually put it in a 16oz cup instead of the 12oz cup so that customers can add milk and creamer if they wish. This is the reason for the inconsistency in the amount of liquid you see in your cup. If you don't like the coffee please feel free to let our staff know to choose another type of coffee and make you another one. Again we're really sorry about this and hope you have a great afternoon friend!
